The last weeks had been wonderful - but nothing could top the birth of my son Luke. :-) I very glad and thankful to all the doctors, midwives and nurses that helped me to bring my baby to life. The last month had been a stressful time. I was suffering under insulin dependent gestational diabetes and a risk of preeclampsia. Both diseases are dangerous for the health of the mother and the unborn child and enforce to take important decisions like the induction of premature birth. For me it was almost unbearable to see that many studies in this field only have a few number of patients, are unclear in the way patients were selected and methods chosen. In guidelines it was claimed that more high quality studies are needed. In the end I was often confused which decision would mean the lowest risk of new health problems or mortal danger for me and my baby. Experiencing this confusion I had seen so much potential for #digitalisation, #datascience, #dataanalytics, #machinelearning and #bigdata in #healthcare. Why not using digital health files for each patient or anomaly detection in cardiotocography? What about automatic estimation of babies growth and health issues in ultrasound videos? Why not starting more high-quality studies based on big data? Why not using machine learning?

15/15 - Jackpot :-) - Today the magic happened and I achieved my last gold medal for becoming a #Kaggle grandmaster with my notebook about the classification of invasive ductal carcinoma: https://lnkd.in/dD74UM6 Thank you for this great experience, your support and feedback that often kept me motivated! I started my journey on #Kaggle 5 years ago with a little baby in my arms within my first maternal leave. My intention at that time was to have some fun and to continue and play with some topics I had learnt during the study of physics. Even though I already had knowledge about #machinelearning and optimisation, it felt like starting from zero with #python and #datavisualisation. I had to accept that it is almost impossible for me to take part in competitions with a baby or toddler at home, a job and interrupted nights. ;-) But I enjoyed to grow and learn by writing notebooks for on- and off-competition datasets. It was never my goal to reach my current state fast as there was so much to discover and the tier-climbing-up kept me motivated to always explore new topics. Looking back now I can definitely say that it was worth it. And now I'm excited to discover the competition branch soon - again with a baby in my arms within my next maternal leave. :-)

Want to learn data science? Avoid the top 10 libraries, the top 10 languages and the top 10 algorithms lists. Start smaller. 10 questions to get you started: 1. Why would one use the t-distribution over the normal? 2. What are the strongest assumptions of OLS? 3. Why do we care about power in experiments? 4. What do frequentists and Bayesians disagree about? 5. When would you use a self join? 6. How can you use a join as a filter condition? 7. What does it mean for R and Python to be vectorized? 8. Why would you use a dictionary vs. a list? Examples? 9. How does the amount of variance affect power? 10. What does it mean to overfit a tree based model? There are so many questions like this that help build the detailed knowledge and domain expertise you need. Answer questions, solve smaller problems. Don't try to tackle an entire language at once. #data #datascience #machinelearning

In case you are wondering, 'why #NLP is so difficult '. This may help you understand. I thought of cleaning the #data. Requirement was to normalize the single-word reviews of the android applications which have rating 1, such that we can prepare target based on the rating. Findings - a. There are reviews which #language detector failed to identify as non-english comment, when such is the case. b. rating is 1 but review is positive, which makes such reviews garbage if you are preparing target using ratings of the app. Should be thrown out of the dataset, if you are building #sentiment #analyzer model or any application for that matter. c. 47 out of 62 unique words bear either opposite connotation or are incomprehensible in english language. Now, imagine that I use some junk word or opposite connotation word in this post. Yes, It will become incomprehensible for humans to read. How can you expect #machine to #comprehend? Nonethless, Machine can manage with junk using the #context (in case review has considerbale length ) if tagging is correct, using advanced #word #representations and #model #architectures but opposite connotation is definitely a big NO. Note - 65-75 % of #reviews are of length less than 5 words. Now, Imagine the nightmare.

The first level involves feature reduction based on some of the important filter methods such as information value, information gain and symmetrical uncertainty, while the second level involves feature subset selection as in a wrapper method. The package displays final set of significant variables with respective variable importance.

Additionally, demographic details of customer were used as features for training the model.
